{{Buddhism}}
{{Religion at Java}}

'''Ashin Jinarakkhita''' (1923-2002),<ref group=web name="LankaWeb" /> born '''Tee Boan-an'''{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} 戴满安 was an [[Chinese Indonesians|Indonesian-born Chinese]]{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} who revived Buddhism in Indonesia.<ref group=web name="LankaWeb" />{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=48}} He was also known as Bhante Ashin, Tizheng Lao Heshang 體正老和尚,<ref group=web name="LankaWeb">[http://www.lankaweb.com/news/items02/160502-4.html In rememberance(sic) of Venerable Ashin Jinarakkhita. The Pioneer of Buddhism Revival in Indonesia]</ref> Teh-ching,{{sfn|Maha Karuna Ch'an|(year unknown)|p=42}} Sukong 師公<ref group=web name="Sukong">[http://www.kadamchoeling.or.id/news.php?nav_id=1&lang=en&id=394&title=Commemoration%20of%20Bhante%20Ashin%E2%80%99s%2010th%20Parinirwana%20Year%20%28by%20Bhadra%20Ruci%29 Commemoration of Bhante Ashin’s 10th Parinirwana Year]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> ("Grandmaster",<ref group=web name="poornima">[http://www.saibabaofindia.com/buddha_poornima_13th_may_speech_phoa_krishnaputra%20.htm WITH HIS GRACE WE CAN ACHIEVE ANYTHING. Buddha Poornima 13 May 2006]</ref> and The Flying Monk.<ref group=web name="devotees" />

==Biography==

===Youth and early career===
Jinarakkhita was born in [[Bogor]], West Java on 23 January 1923<ref group=web name="LankaWeb" /> as Tee Boan-an 戴满安,{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} the third son of The Hong Gie and Tan Sep Moy.<ref group=web name="devotees" /> 
According to Juangari, as a young boy Tee Boan-an was already interested in yoga and "mystic powers".<ref group=web name="devotees" /> As a boy, he met a Theosophist from the Netherlands, who encouraged him to read "The Ancient Wisdom" and "The Secret Doctrines".<ref group=web name="devotees" /> When he was a teenager, Tee Boan-an practiced meditation at Gede Mountain and Salak Mountain, and visited "virtuous people" and Viharas to gain spiritual knowledge.<ref group=web name="devotees" />

After attending the HBS at Jakarta and the Technical School in Bandung, he left in 1946 for the Netherlands to study chemistry at [[Groningen University]].<ref group=web name="LankaWeb" /> There he also continued his interest in Theosophy.<ref group=web name="devotees" /> He also learnt Pali and Sanskrit languages from Dr. Van Der Leeuw,<ref group=web name="devotees" /> and acquired fluency in English, German, French, and Dutch.<ref group=web name="devotees" /> During holidays, he went to France, where he had the opportunity to attend lectures by [[Jiddu Krishnamurti]].<ref group=web name="devotees" />

In 1951<ref group=web name="devotees" /> he returned to Indonesia, where he worked as a teacher at several secondary schools in Jakarta,<ref group=web name="LankaWeb" /> but also took an active interest in religion.

===Buddhist ordination===
{{See also|Theosophical Society|Buddhist modernism|Vipassana movement}}

Tee Boan-an became president of the Indonesian Sam Kauw Union<ref group=web name="LankaWeb" /><ref group=web name="devotees" />{{refn|group=note|See <ref group=web name="Ditthi">[http://www.buddhismandaustralia.com/index.php/en/articles/articles-2012/102-buddhism-in-indonesia-past-and-present-ven-ditthisampanno.html Ven. Ditthisampanno, ''Buddhism in Indonesia, Past and Present''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309233604/http://www.buddhismandaustralia.com/index.php/en/articles/articles-2012/102-buddhism-in-indonesia-past-and-present-ven-ditthisampanno.html |date=9 March 2013 }}</ref> for more info on the Sam Kauw Union}} as well as the vice-president of the central committee of the Indonesian Theosophy Youth.<ref group=web name="LankaWeb" /><ref group=web name="devotees" />{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} Buddhism was reintroduced in Indonesia in the beginning of the 20th century by the [[Theosophical Society]],{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} which played a central role in the popularisation of Buddhism in the west, and the revival of Buddhism in Sri Lanka.{{sfn|McMahan|2008}} In Indonesia the Theosophical Society found adherents among the Dutch colonials, Chinese immigrants, and Indonesian noblemen.{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} Buddhism spread in the form of Theravada and Mahayana.{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} Theravada followers had contacts with Buddhist monasteries in Sri Lanka, Burma and Thailand, while Chinese Mahayana priests were invited by the Indonesian-Chinese Buddhist communities.{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}}

Tee Boan-an received ordination as a Mahayana [[Ch'an]]<ref group=web name="Ditthi" /> novice monk on 29 July 1953, and received the name Tizheng 體正 (Te Cheng) from the Chinese Mahayana priest Benqing (Pen Ching/Pen Cheng) Lao Heshang,<ref group=web name="LankaWeb" />{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} from the [[Guanghua Temple (Putian)|Guanghua Monastery]] in [[Putian]], China.<ref group=web name="Braak2015">[http://www.vriendenvanboeddhisme.nl/2015/china.html Andre van der Braak, ''Vijf bezoeken aan China verder], Vrienden van het Boeddhisme, januari 2015]</ref>{{refn|group=note|本清老和尚,<ref group=web>[http://remajabuddhist.wordpress.com/buddhayana/ Buddhayana]</ref> also known as Y.A. Mahasthavira Arya Mula.,<ref group=web name="devotees" /> Pen Ching Lau He Sang (pinyin: Benqing Lao Heshang),{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} Pun-Cheng,{{sfn|Maha Karuna Ch'an|(year unknown)|p=42}} and Pen Cheng.{{sfn|Verboven|1992}} Pen Cheng (1878<ref group=web name="devotees" /> or 1887{{sfn|Verboven|1992}}-1962) was born at Wu Chen Li village, at Putian district, Fujian, China.<ref group=web name="devotees" /> He was trained in Kuang Hua Ssu 廣化寺 (Kuang Hua, [[Guanghua Temple (Putian)|Guanghua Temple]], "Vast Influence",{{sfn|Hsüan Hua|2003|p=189}} in Fo Tiën{{sfn|Verboven|1992}} ([[Fujian]]), a monastery which was influenced by [[Hsu Yun]], abbot of Ku Shan Ssu (Gu Shan) monastery in Fo Tiën (see also Charles Luk (Lu K'uan Yü), "Chan and Zen Teaching"{{sfn|Verboven|1992}}). Benqing came to Indonesia in the beginning of the 20th century. {{sfn|Verboven|1992}} This was in the time of the socalled Buddhist Revival, when, under influence of the western culture, attempt were being made to revitalize Chinese Buddhism.{{sfn|Huai-Chin|1999}} Most notable were the [[Humanistic Buddhism]] of [[Taixu]], and the revival of [[Chinese Chán]] by [[Hsu Yun]].{{sfn|Huai-Chin|1999}}}} Eventually, Tizheng received dharma transmission from Benqing.{{sfn|Verboven|1992}}<ref group=web>[http://eng.longquanzs.org/scholars/60599.htm Voice of Longquan, ''Ton Lathouwers'']</ref>

After the Communists took over power in China in 1949, Buddhist monasteries were closed in China, and Indonesia tried to diminish Chinese influences in Indonesia.{{sfn|Verboven|1992}} For these reasons, further Ch'an-training in China was problematic,{{sfn|Verboven|1992}} 
and Benqing sent Tizheng to Burma in 1953, where he practiced [[satipatthana]] meditation under [[Mahasi Sayadaw]].<ref group=web name="Ditthi" />{{sfn|Verboven|1992}} Tizheng was ordained as a Theravada monk in 1954, and received the name Ashin Jinarakkhita.{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} The same year he returned to Indonesia,

===Buddhist Revival===
Jinarakkhita was instrumental in the revival of Buddhism in Indonesia. He realised that Buddhism had to adapt to Indonesian culture to survive; otherwise it would remain a foreign "fremdkörper".{{sfn|Verboven|1992}}{{refn|group=note|The same strategy was being followed by Catholic missionaries like the [[Divine Word Missionaries]] (SVD) and the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]], who were aware of the value of the Javanese culture and identity.{{sfn|Ricklefs|2007|p=122-124}}}}

In 1955 Jinarakkhita formed the first Indonesian Buddhist lay organisation, Persaudaraan Upasaka Upasika Indonesia (PUUI).{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} In 1957, the PUUI was integrated into the Indonesian Buddhist Association (Perhimpunan Buddhis Indonesia, Perbudi),{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} in which both Theravada and Mahayana priesthood were united.{{sfn|Melton|2010|p=1449}} Nowadays, the PUUI is called Majelis Buddhayana Indonesia (MBI).<ref group=web name="Buddhayana">[http://gabveg.wordpress.com/budhhayana/ Buddhayana]</ref>

In 1960 Jinarakkhita established the Sangha Suci Indonesia, as a monastic organisation. In 1963 the name was changed to Maha Sangha of Indonesia, and in 1974 the name was change into Sangha Agung Indonesia. It is a community of monastics from the Theravada, Mahayana and Tantrayana traditions.<ref group=web name="Buddhayana" /><ref group=web name="Ditthi" />{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=49}}

In 1965, after a [[Transition to the New Order|coup-attempt]], Buddhist organisations had to comply with the first principle of the Indonesian state ideology, ''Pancasila'', the belief in one supreme God.{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=48}} All organisations that doubted or denied the existence of God were outlawed.{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=297}} this posed a problem for Indonesian Buddhism, which was solved by Jinarakkhita by presenting [[nibbana]] as the Theravada "God", and Adi-Buddha, the primaeval Buddha of the region's previous Mantrayana Buddhism, as the Mahayana "God".{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=297}} According to Jinarakkhita, the concept of ''Adi Buddha'' was found in the tenth-century Javanese Buddhist text ''Sang Hyang Kamhayanikan''.{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=48}}

Another important factor in the Buddhist Revival was the use of a new category of lay Buddhist teachers.{{sfn|Lathouwers|2008}} Those were older Buddhists without a formal [[dharma transmission]] or authorisation, but with a lot of life-experience. Those elder teachers were sanctioned by Jinarakkhita, and instituted new meditation-centers, and organised meetings and lectures.{{sfn|Lathouwers|2008}}{{refn|group=note|The use of lay-teachers was not new in Indonesia. In conjunction with missionaries from the [[Divine Word Missionaries]] (SVD) and the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]], "lay-apostles" in the first half of the 20th century spread and practiced the Gosple.{{sfn|Missiemuseum Steyl|year unknown}} Exemplary are the Schmutzer family, who established the Catholic [[Ganjuran Church]] in Ganjuran, Bantul, Java.{{sfn|Missiemuseum Steyl|year unknown}}}}

===Death===
Jinarakkhita died on Thursday 18 April 2002 in Pluit Hospital, North Jakarta. His ashes and relics were brought back to Sakyavanaram Temple at Cipendawa Cliff, Pacet, [[Cianjur]] (between Jakarta and Bandung), [[West Java]], where Jinarakkhita lived.<ref group=web name="LankaWeb" />

==Teachings==
Jinarakkhita had a liberal teaching on Buddhism.{{sfn|Lathouwers|2008}} According to Jinarakkhita, ''orang suci'' ("saints") can be found everywhere,{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=48}} and religious experience is personal and unique.{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=48}} Each person has to pursue his or her own path.{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=48}} In his teachings he often quoted non-Buddhists, such as [[Ranggawarsita]],{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=48}} and he admired [[Sai Baba of Shirdi|Sai Baba]].{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=48}}<ref group=web name="devotees">[http://www.indiadivine.org/showthread.php/248041-THE-DEVOTEES-OF-SAI-BABA-A-Short-Biography-of-Su-Kong The devotees of Sai Baba - A Short Biography of Su Kong]</ref>

Love, as represented by [[Guanyin]], is essential:
{{quote|Duty is most important. If you practice love, there is no war, no hate. Truth is love. Buddhism is a religion of love. Jesus Christ sacrificed his Life for the sake of love. All religions are based on love.<ref group=web name="devotees" />}}

==Students==
Jinarakkhita had students and followers in both Indonesia and other countries.{{sfn|Suryadinata|1995|p=48-49}} One of them is Ton Lathouwers, a Dutch lay student who received dharma transmission in the Rinzai-lineage in 1987,{{sfn|Verboven|1992}} and founded the ''Maha Karuna Ch'an'' organisation in the Netherlands.<ref group=web name="MahaKaruna">[http://www.mahakarunachan.be/welkom/introduction-in-english/ Maha Karuna Ch'an] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425150903/http://www.mahakarunachan.be/welkom/introduction-in-english/ |date=25 April 2012 }}</ref>

