'''François-André-Adrien Pluquet''' (14 June 1716 – 18 September 1790) was a French theologian and philosopher. Best known for his ''Dictionary of [[Heresy|Heresies]]'' (1762), he also wrote treatises on [[determinism]], [[sociability]] and luxury.
==Life== Pluquet was born in [[Bayeux]]. He studied in [[Caen]] and [[Paris]], becoming a licencié of the [[Sorbonne]] in 1750. He worked as tutor to the abbé de Choiseul, younger brother of the [[César Gabriel de Choiseul|Duc de Choiseul]], who provided him with a pension allowing him to pursue independent study.<ref name="Laursen2002">{{cite book|author=Patrick Coleman|editor=John Christian Laursen|title=Histories of Heresy in the 17th and 18th Centuries: For, Against, and Beyond Persecution and Toleration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1JCy9rdpbo0C&pg=PA224|accessdate=25 November 2012|year=2002|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-312-29404-5|pages=224–5|chapter=The Enlightened Orthodoxy of the Abbé Pluquet}}</ref>
==Works== * ''Examen du fatalisme'' (Examination of determinism), 1757 * ''Dictionnaire des hérésies, des erreurs et des schismes'' (Dictionary of heresies, errors and schisms), 1762 * ''De la sociabilité'' (On sociability), 1767 * (tr. from [[Latin language|Latin]]) ''Les livres classiques de l'Empire de la Chine'' (The classical books of the Chinese Empire) by François Noël. 7 vols, 1784-86. * ''Traité philosophique et politique sur le luxe'' (Philosophical and political treatise on luxury), 2 vols, 1786
